# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: phpunit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] This appendix lists the various assertion methods that are available.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] PHPUnit’s assertions are implemented in `PHPUnit\Framework\Assert`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] `PHPUnit\Framework\TestCase` inherits from `PHPUnit\Framework\Assert`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] The assertion methods are declared static and can be invoked from any context using `PHPUnit\Framework\Assert::assertTrue()`, for instance, or using `$this->assertTrue()` or `self::assertTrue()`, for instance, in a class that extends `PHPUnit\Framework\TestCase`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] You can even use global function wrappers such as `assertTrue()`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] A common question, especially from developers new to PHPUnit, is whether using `$this->assertTrue()` or `self::assertTrue()`, for instance, is “the right way” to invoke an assertion.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] The short answer is: there is no right way.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] For most people it just “feels right” to use `$this->assertTrue()` because the test method is invoked on a test object.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] The fact that the assertion methods are declared static allows for (re)using them outside the scope of a test object.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Lastly, the global function wrappers allow developers to type less characters (`assertTrue()` instead of `$this->assertTrue()` or `self::assertTrue()`).
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$condition` is `false`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] `assertNotTrue()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$condition` is `true`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] `assertNotFalse()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the two variables `$expected` and `$actual` do not have the same type and value.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] `assertNotSame()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the two variables `$expected` and `$actual` do not reference the same object.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Identity is checked using the `===` operator.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if two arrays are not identical while only considering array elements for which the keys have been specified.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if two arrays are not identical while only ignoring array elements for which the keys have been specified.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the two variables `$expected` and `$actual` are not equal.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] `assertNotEquals()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Equality is checked using the `==` operator, but more specialized comparisons are used for specific argument types for `$expected` and `$actual`, see below.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the two points in time represented by the two `DateTimeInterface` objects `$expected` and `$actual` are not equal.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the uncommented canonical form of the XML documents represented by the two `DOMDocument` objects `$expected` and `$actual` are not equal.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the two objects `$expected` and `$actual` do not have equal property values.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the two arrays `$expected` and `$actual` are not equal.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] The contents of `$expected` and `$actual` are canonicalized before they are compared.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] For instance, when the two variables `$expected` and `$actual` are arrays, then these arrays are sorted before they are compared.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] When `$expected` and `$actual` are objects, each object is converted to an array containing all private, protected and public properties.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] `assertNotEqualsCanonicalizing()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Differences in casing are ignored for the comparison of `$expected` and `$actual`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] `assertNotEqualsIgnoringCase()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the absolute difference between `$expected` and `$actual` is greater than `$delta`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Please read “What Every Computer Scientist Should Know About Floating-Point Arithmetic” to understand why `$delta` is necessary.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] `assertNotEqualsWithDelta()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$actual` is not equal to `$expected` according to `$actual->$method($expected)`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] It is a bad practice to use `assertEquals()` (and its inverse, `assertNotEquals()`) on objects without registering a custom comparator that customizes how objects are compared.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Unfortunately, though, implementing custom comparators for each and every object you want to assert in your tests is inconvenient at best.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] The most common use case for custom comparators are Value Objects.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] These objects usually have an `equals(self $other): bool` method (or a method just like that but with a different name) for comparing two instances of the Value Object’s type.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] `assertObjectNotEquals()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] If any of the aforementioned assumptions is not fulfilled or if `$actual->$method($expected)` returns `false` then the assertion fails.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the file specified by `$expected` does not have the same contents as the file specified by `$actual`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] `assertFileNotEquals()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if two arrays are not equal while only considering array elements for which the keys have been specified.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p01] Reports an error identified by `$message` if two arrays are not equal while only ignoring array elements for which the keys have been specified.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$array` does not have the `$key`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertArrayNotHasKey()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$needle` is not an element of `$haystack`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertNotContains()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Whether `$needle` is an element of `$haystack` is checked using the `===` operator.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] You can use `assertContainsEquals()` (and `assertNotContainsEquals()`) if you need the comparison logic implemented by the `==` operator.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only variables of type `$type`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `$isNativeType` is a flag used to indicate whether `$type` is a native PHP type.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] These are the strings supported for `$type` when `$isNativeType` is `true`: `array`, `bool`, `boolean`, `callable`, `double`, `float`, `int`, `integer`, `iterable`, `null`, `numeric`, `object`, `real`, `resource`, `scalar`, or `string`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertNotContainsOnly()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] As of PHPUnit 11.5, the `assertContainsOnly()` method is soft-deprecated, meaning its declaration is annotated with `@deprecated` so that IDEs and static analysis tools can warn about its usage.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Starting with PHPUnit 12, using the `assertContainsOnly()` method will trigger a deprecation warning.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] The method will be removed in PHPUnit 13.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only values of type `array`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyArray()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only values of type `bool`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyBool()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only values of type `callable`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyCallable()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only values of type `float`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyFloat()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only values of type `int`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyInt()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only values of type `iterable`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyIterable()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only values of type `null`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyNull()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only values of type `numeric`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyNumeric()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only values of type `object`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyObject()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only values of type `resource`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyResource()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only values of type `resource (closed)`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyClosedResource()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only values of type `scalar`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyScalar()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only values of type `string`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyString()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$haystack` does not contain only instances of class or interface `$type`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertContainsNotOnlyInstancesOf()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$object` does not have a property with the name `$propertyName`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertObjectNotHasProperty()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the number of elements in `$haystack` is not `$expectedCount`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertNotCount()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Please note that `assertCount()` and `assertNotCount()` do not support generators.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Generators can only be iterated over once and they cannot be cloned.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Passing a generator to `assertCount()` or `assertNotCount()` would therefore change the state of something that is supposed to be only verified.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the sizes of `$actual` and `$expected` are not the same.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertNotSameSize()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Please note that `assertSameSize()` and `assertNotSameSize()` do not support generators.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Passing a generator to `assertSameSize()` or `assertNotSameSize()` would therefore change the state of something that is supposed to be only verified.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$actual` is not empty.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] `assertNotEmpty()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Please note that `assertEmpty()` and `assertNotEmpty()` do not support generators.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Passing a generator to `assertEmpty()` or `assertNotEmpty()` would therefore change the state of something that is supposed to be only verified.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the value of `$actual` is not greater than the value of `$expected`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the value of `$actual` is not greater than or equal to the value of `$expected`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the value of `$actual` is not less than the value of `$expected`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the value of `$actual` is not less than or equal to the value of `$expected`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p02] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$actual` is not an instance of `$expected`.
