[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the `$string` does not start with `$prefix`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] `assertStringStartsNotWith()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the `$string` does not end with `$suffix`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] `assertStringEndsNotWith()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$needle` is not a substring of `$haystack`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] `assertStringNotContainsString()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] `assertStringContainsStringIgnoringLineEndings()` takes the same arguments and can be used if line endings should be ignored.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] Differences in casing are ignored when `$needle` is searched for in `$haystack`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] This also works for Unicode characters with diacritics (accents, umlauts, circumflex, etc.) as long as both strings have the same Normalization Form.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] `assertStringNotContainsStringIgnoringCase()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the two strings `$expected` and `$actual` are not equal while ignoring line endings.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] Reports an error identified by `$message` if `$string` does not match the regular expression `$pattern`.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] `assertDoesNotMatchRegularExpression()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the `$string` does not match the `$format` string.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] `assertStringNotMatchesFormat()` is the inverse of this assertion and takes the same arguments.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] As of PHPUnit 10.4, the `assertStringNotMatchesFormat()` method is soft-deprecated, meaning its declaration is annotated with `@deprecated` so that IDEs and static analysis tools can warn about its usage.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] Starting with PHPUnit 11, using the `assertStringNotMatchesFormat()` method will trigger a deprecation warning.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] The method will be removed in PHPUnit 12.
[src:phpunit/assertions-p03] Reports an error identified by `$message` if the `$string` does not match the contents of the `$formatFile`.
