[src:phpunit/phpunit] PHPUnit is based on the idea that developers should be able to find mistakes in their newly committed code quickly and assert that no code regression has occurred in other parts of the code base.
[src:phpunit/phpunit] Much like other unit testing frameworks, PHPUnit uses assertions to verify that the behavior of the specific component - or *"unit"* - being tested behaves as expected.
[src:phpunit/phpunit] The goal of unit testing is to isolate each part of the program and show that the individual parts are correct.
[src:phpunit/phpunit] A unit test provides a strict, written contract that the piece of code must satisfy.
[src:phpunit/phpunit] As a result, unit tests find problems early in the development cycle.
[src:phpunit/phpunit] PHPUnit can output test results in a number of different formats, including JUnit XML and TestDox.
[src:phpunit/phpunit] A vulnerability that allowed attackers to execute remote code via PHPUnit was discovered in late 2017.
[src:phpunit/phpunit] By sending a payload of PHP code to a file that is part of PHPUnit, an attacker could execute PHP code on the webserver.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing describes tests that are run at the unit-level to contrast testing at the integration or system level.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing, as a principle for testing separately smaller parts of large software systems, dates back to the early days of software engineering.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In June 1956 at US Navy's Symposium on Advanced Programming Methods for Digital Computers, H.D.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] It featured a specification-based approach where the coding phase was followed by "parameter testing" to validate component subprograms against their specification, followed then by an "assembly testing" for parts put together.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In 1964, a similar approach is described for the software of the Mercury project, where individual units developed by different programmers underwent "unit tests" before being integrated together.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In 1969, testing methodologies appear more structured, with unit tests, component tests and integration tests collectively validating individual parts written separately and their progressive assembly into larger blocks.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Some public standards adopted in the late 1960s, such as MIL-STD-483 and MIL-STD-490, contributed further to a wide acceptance of unit testing in large projects.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing was in those times interactive or automated, using either coded tests or capture and replay testing tools.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In 1989, Kent Beck described a testing framework for Smalltalk (later called SUnit) in "Simple Smalltalk Testing: With Patterns".
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In 1997, Kent Beck and Erich Gamma developed and released JUnit, a unit test framework that became popular with Java developers.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Google embraced automated testing around 2005–2006.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] A unit is defined as a single behaviour exhibited by the system under test (SUT), usually corresponding to a requirement.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] While a unit may correspond to a single function or module (in procedural programming) or a single method or class (in object-oriented programming), functions/methods and modules/classes do not necessarily correspond to units.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] From the system requirements perspective only the perimeter of the system is relevant, thus only entry points to externally visible system behaviours define units.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit tests can be performed manually or via automated test execution.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Automated tests include benefits such as: running tests often, running tests without staffing cost, and consistent and repeatable testing.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Testing is often performed by the programmer who writes and modifies the code under test.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing may be viewed as part of the process of writing code.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] During development, a programmer may code criteria, or results that are known to be good, into the test to verify the unit's correctness.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] During test execution, frameworks log tests that fail any criterion and report them in a summary.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] For this, the most commonly used approach is test - function - expected value.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Test cases underlie testing that is methodical rather than haphazard.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] A battery of test cases can be built to produce the desired coverage of the software being tested.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Formally defined test cases allow the same tests to be run repeatedly against successive versions of the software, allowing for effective and consistent regression testing.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] A test double is software used in software test automation that satisfies a dependency so that the test need not depend on production code.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] A test double provides functionality via an interface that the software under test cannot distinguish from production code.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] A parameterized test is a test that accepts a set of values that can be used to enable the test to run with multiple, different input values.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] A testing framework that supports parametrized tests supports a way to encode parameter sets and to run the test with each set.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Use of parametrized tests can reduce test code duplication.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Parameterized tests are supported by TestNG, JUnit, XUnit and NUnit, as well as in various JavaScript test frameworks.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Parameters for the unit tests may be coded manually or in some cases are automatically generated by the test framework.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In recent years support was added for writing more powerful (unit) tests, leveraging the concept of theories, test cases that execute the same steps, but using test data generated at runtime, unlike regular parameterized tests that use the same execution steps with input sets that are pre-defined.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Test code needs access to the code it is testing, but testing should not compromise normal design goals such as information hiding, encapsulation and the separation of concerns.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] To enable access to code not exposed in the external API, unit tests can be located in the same project or module as the code being tested.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In object oriented design this still may not provide access to private data and methods.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Therefore, extra work may be necessary for unit tests.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In Java and other languages, a developer can use reflection to access private fields and methods.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Alternatively, an inner class can be used to hold the unit tests so they have visibility of the enclosing class's members and attributes.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In the .NET Framework and some other programming languages, partial classes may be used to expose private methods and data for the tests to access.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] It is important that code solely for accommodating tests does not remain in the production code.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In C and other languages, compiler directives such as `#if DEBUG ... #endif` can be placed around such additional classes and indeed all other test-related code to prevent them being compiled into the released code.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] This means the released code is not exactly the same as what was unit tested.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] The regular running of fewer but more comprehensive, end-to-end, integration tests on the final release build can ensure (among other things) that no production code exists that subtly relies on aspects of the test harness.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] There is some debate among developers, as to whether it is wise to test private methods and data anyway.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Some argue that private members are a mere implementation detail that may change, and should be allowed to do so without breaking numbers of tests.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Thus it should be sufficient to test any class through its public interface or through its subclass interface, which some languages call the "protected" interface.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Others say that crucial aspects of functionality may be implemented in private methods and testing them directly offers advantage of smaller and more direct unit tests.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In test-driven development (TDD), unit tests are written before the related production code is written.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Starting with a failing test, then adds *just enough* production code to make the test pass, then refactors the code as makes sense and then repeats by adding another failing test.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing is intended to ensure that the units meet their design and behave as intended.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] By writing tests first for the smallest testable units, then the compound behaviors between those, one can build up comprehensive tests for complex applications.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] One goal of unit testing is to isolate each part of the program and show that the individual parts are correct.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing finds problems early in the development cycle.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] This includes both bugs in the programmer's implementation and flaws or missing parts of the specification for the unit.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] The process of writing a thorough set of tests forces the author to think through inputs, outputs, and error conditions, and thus more crisply define the unit's desired behavior.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] The cost of finding a bug before coding begins or when the code is first written is considerably lower than the cost of detecting, identifying, and correcting the bug later.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Bugs in released code may also cause costly problems for the end-users of the software.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Code can be impossible or difficult to unit test if poorly written, thus unit testing can force developers to structure functions and objects in better ways.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing enables more frequent releases in software development.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] By testing individual components in isolation, developers can quickly identify and address issues, leading to faster iteration and release cycles.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing allows the programmer to refactor code or upgrade system libraries at a later date, and make sure the module still works correctly (e.g., in regression testing).
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] The procedure is to write test cases for all functions and methods so that whenever a change causes a fault, it can be identified quickly.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit tests detect changes which may break a design contract.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing may reduce uncertainty in the units themselves and can be used in a bottom-up testing style approach.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] By testing the parts of a program first and then testing the sum of its parts, integration testing becomes much easier.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Some programmers contend that unit tests provide a form of documentation of the code.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Developers wanting to learn what functionality is provided by a unit, and how to use it, can review the unit tests to gain an understanding of it.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Test cases can embody characteristics that are critical to the success of the unit.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] These characteristics can indicate appropriate/inappropriate use of a unit as well as negative behaviors that are to be trapped by the unit.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] A test case documents these critical characteristics, although many software development environments do not rely solely upon code to document the product in development.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In some processes, the act of writing tests and the code under test, plus associated refactoring, may take the place of formal design.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Each unit test can be seen as a design element specifying classes, methods, and observable behavior.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Testing will not catch every error in the program, because it cannot evaluate every execution path in any but the most trivial programs.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] This problem is a superset of the halting problem, which is undecidable.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Additionally, unit testing by definition only tests the functionality of the units themselves.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Therefore, it will not catch integration errors or broader system-level errors (such as functions performed across multiple units, or non-functional test areas such as performance).
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing should be done in conjunction with other software testing activities, as they can only show the presence or absence of particular errors; they cannot prove a complete absence of errors.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] To guarantee correct behavior for every execution path and every possible input, and ensure the absence of errors, other techniques are required, namely the application of formal methods to prove that a software component has no unexpected behavior.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] An elaborate hierarchy of unit tests does not equal integration testing.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Integration with peripheral units should be included in integration tests, but not in unit tests.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Integration testing typically still relies heavily on humans testing manually; high-level or global-scope testing can be difficult to automate, such that manual testing often appears faster and cheaper.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Software testing is a combinatorial problem.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] For example, every Boolean decision statement requires at least two tests: one with an outcome of "true" and one with an outcome of "false".
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] As a result, for every line of code written, programmers often need 3 to 5 lines of test code.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] This obviously takes time and its investment may not be worth the effort.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] There are problems that cannot easily be tested at all – for example those that are nondeterministic or involve multiple threads.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In addition, code for a unit test is as likely to be buggy as the code it is testing.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Another challenge related to writing the unit tests is the difficulty of setting up realistic and useful tests.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] It is necessary to create relevant initial conditions so the part of the application being tested behaves like part of the complete system.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] If these initial conditions are not set correctly, the test will not be exercising the code in a realistic context, which diminishes the value and accuracy of unit test results.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] To obtain the intended benefits from unit testing, rigorous discipline is needed throughout the software development process.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] It is essential to keep careful records not only of the tests that have been performed, but also of all changes that have been made to the source code of this or any other unit in the software.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Use of a version control system is essential.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] If a later version of the unit fails a particular test that it had previously passed, the version-control software can provide a list of the source code changes (if any) that have been applied to the unit since that time.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] It is also essential to implement a sustainable process for ensuring that test case failures are reviewed regularly and addressed immediately.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] If such a process is not implemented and ingrained into the team's workflow, the application will evolve out of sync with the unit test suite, increasing false positives and reducing the effectiveness of the test suite.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing embedded system software presents challenges because the software is being developed on a different platform than the one it will eventually run on, making it difficult to run a test program in the actual deployment environment, as is possible with desktop programs.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit tests tend to be easiest when a method has input parameters and some output.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] It is not as easy to create unit tests when a major function of the method is to interact with something external to the application.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] For example, a method that will work with a database might require a mock up of database interactions to be created, which probably won't be as comprehensive as the real database interactions.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Below is an example of a JUnit test suite.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] The test suite uses assert statements to verify the expected result of various input values to the `sum` method.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Using unit-tests as a design specification has one significant advantage over other design methods: The design document (the unit-tests themselves) can itself be used to verify the implementation.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] The tests will never pass unless the developer implements a solution according to the design.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing lacks some of the accessibility of a diagrammatic specification such as a UML diagram, but they may be generated from the unit test using automated tools.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Most modern languages have free tools (usually available as extensions to IDEs).
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Free tools, like those based on the xUnit framework, outsource to another system the graphical rendering of a view for human consumption.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing is the cornerstone of extreme programming, which relies on an automated unit testing framework.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] This automated unit testing framework can be either third party, e.g., xUnit, or created within the development group.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Extreme programming uses the creation of unit tests for test-driven development.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] The developer writes a unit test that exposes either a software requirement or a defect.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] This test will fail because either the requirement isn't implemented yet, or because it intentionally exposes a defect in the existing code.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Then, the developer writes the simplest code to make the test, along with other tests, pass.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Most code in a system is unit tested, but not necessarily all paths through the code.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Extreme programming mandates a "test everything that can possibly break" strategy, over the traditional "test every execution path" method.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] This leads developers to develop fewer tests than classical methods, but this isn't really a problem, more a restatement of fact, as classical methods have rarely ever been followed methodically enough for all execution paths to have been thoroughly tested.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Extreme programming simply recognizes that testing is rarely exhaustive (because it is often too expensive and time-consuming to be economically viable) and provides guidance on how to effectively focus limited resources.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Crucially, the test code is considered a first class project artifact in that it is maintained at the same quality as the implementation code, with all duplication removed.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Developers release unit testing code to the code repository in conjunction with the code it tests.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Extreme programming's thorough unit testing allows the benefits mentioned above, such as simpler and more confident code development and refactoring, simplified code integration, accurate documentation, and more modular designs.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] These unit tests are also constantly run as a form of regression test.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Unit testing is also critical to the concept of Emergent Design, which develops software design iteratively through short test-driven development cycles of writing a unit test, making it pass, and refactoring; unit tests provide the regression safety net that makes continuous refactoring safe.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] An automated testing framework provides features for automating test execution and can accelerate writing and running tests.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Frameworks have been developed for a wide variety of programming languages.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Generally, frameworks are third-party, not distributed with a compiler or integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Tests can be written without using a framework to exercise the code under test using assertions, exception handling, and other control flow mechanisms to verify behavior and report failure.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Some note that testing without a framework is valuable since there is a barrier to entry for the adoption of a framework, and that having some tests is better than none – but once a framework is in place, adding tests can be easier.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] In some frameworks advanced test features are missing and must be hand-coded.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Some programming languages directly support unit testing.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Their grammar allows the direct declaration of unit tests without importing a library (whether third party or standard).
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Additionally, the Boolean conditions of the unit tests can be expressed in the same syntax as Boolean expressions used in non-unit test code, such as what is used for `if` and `while` statements.
[src:phpunit/unit-testing] Some languages do not have built-in unit-testing support but have established unit testing libraries or frameworks.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] `GreeterTest` inherits from `PHPUnit\Framework\TestCase`.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] The tests are public methods that are named `test*`.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Alternatively, you can use the `PHPUnit\Framework\Attributes\Test` attribute on a method to mark it as a test method.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] See the section on the Test attribute for details.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Inside the test methods, assertion methods such as `assertSame()` (see Assertions) are used to assert that an actual value matches an expected value, for instance.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Example 2.3 shows how to use the `expectException()` method to test whether an exception is thrown by the code under test.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] The `expectException()` method has to be used **before** the exception you expect to be thrown is thrown.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Ideally, `expectException()` is called immediately before the code is called that is expected to throw the exception.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] In addition to the `expectException()` method the `expectExceptionCode()`, `expectExceptionMessage()`, and `expectExceptionMessageMatches()` methods exist to set up expectations for exceptions raised by the code under test.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Note that `expectExceptionMessage()` asserts that the `$actual` message contains the `$expected` message and does not perform an exact string comparison.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Asserting return values and expecting exceptions are two of the three most commonly performed operations in a test method.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] The verification of side effects in object collaboration is discussed in the chapter on Test Doubles.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] A test method can accept arbitrary arguments.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] These arguments are to be provided by one or more data provider methods (`additionProvider()` in the example shown below).
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] The data provider method to be used is specified using the `PHPUnit\Framework\Attributes\DataProvider` or the `PHPUnit\Framework\Attributes\DataProviderExternal` attribute.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] A data provider method must be `public` and `static` and its name must not start with `test`.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] It must return a value that is iterable, either an array or an object that implements the `Traversable` interface.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] In each iteration step, it must yield an array.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] For each of these arrays, the test method will be called with the contents of the array as its arguments.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] It is useful to name each one with a string key.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Output will be more verbose as it will contain that name of a dataset that breaks a test.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] You can make the test output more verbose by defining a sentence and using the test’s parameter names as placeholders (`$a`, `$b` and `$expected` in the example above) with the TestDox attribute (or the @testdox annotation).
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] You can also refer to the name of a named data set with `$_dataName`.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] When a test receives input from both a data provider method and from one or more tests it depends on, the arguments from the data provider will come before the ones from depended-upon tests.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] The arguments from depended-upon tests will be the same for each data set.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] When a test depends on a test that uses data providers, the depending test will be executed when the test it depends upon is successful for at least one data set.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] The result of a test that uses data providers cannot be injected into a depending test.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] All data providers, including those for test methods that will not be run due to `--filter` or `--exclude-group`, for example, are executed before both the call to the `setUpBeforeClass()` static method and the first call to the `setUp()` method.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] You cannot access any properties of the actual test case object in methods such as `setUpBeforeClass()` or `setUp()` within a data provider.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] No code coverage data is collected while data provider methods are executed.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] The data sets provided by a data provider method should only contain (arrays of) scalar values, immutable value objects, or Test Stubs.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Services or large objects graphs should not be created in a data provider method.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Mock Objects cannot be created in a data provider method.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Sometimes you want to assert that the execution of a method, for instance, generates an expected output (via `echo` or `print`, for example).
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] The `PHPUnit\Framework\TestCase` class uses PHP’s Output Buffering feature to provide the functionality that is necessary for this.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Example 2.7 shows how to use the `expectOutputString()` method to set the expected output.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] If this expected output is not generated, the test will be counted as a failure.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Only one expectation on output can be configured.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] `expectOutputString()` and `expectOutputRegex()` cannot be combined and must not be called more than once.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] to keep track of the tests that you have to write.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Do yourself a favour and never use pointless names such as `testSomething` for your test methods.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] The problem with empty test methods is that they cannot fail and may be misinterpreted as a success.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] This misinterpretation leads to the test reports being useless – you cannot see whether a test is actually successful or just not implemented yet.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Calling `$this->assertTrue(false)`, for instance, in the unfinished test method does not help either, since then the test will be interpreted as a failure.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] This would be just as wrong as interpreting an unimplemented test as a success.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] If we think of a successful test as a green light and a test failure as a red light, then we need an additional yellow light to mark a test as being incomplete or not yet implemented.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Not all tests can be run in every environment.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Consider, for instance, a database abstraction layer that has several drivers for the different database systems it supports.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] The tests for the MySQL driver can only be run if a MySQL server is available.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Example 2.9 shows a test case class, `DatabaseTest`, that contains one test method, `testConnection()`.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] In the test case class’ `setUp()` template method we check whether the MySQLi extension is available and use the `markTestSkipped()` method to skip the test if it is not.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] All attributes listed above are declared in the `PHPUnit\Framework\Attributes` namespace.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] PHPUnit supports the declaration of explicit dependencies between test methods.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Such dependencies do not define the order in which the test methods are to be executed but they allow the returning of an instance of the test fixture by a producer and passing it to the dependent consumers.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] In the example above, the first test, `testEmpty()`, creates a new array and asserts that it is empty.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] The test then returns the fixture as its result.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] The second test, `testPush()`, depends on `testEmpty()` and is passed the result of that depended-upon test as its argument.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Finally, `testPop()` depends upon `testPush()`.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] The return value yielded by a producer is passed “as-is” to its consumers by default.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] This means that when a producer returns an object, a reference to that object is passed to the consumers.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Instead of a reference either (a) a (deep) copy via `DependsUsingDeepClone`, or (b) a (normal shallow) clone (based on PHP keyword `clone`) via `DependsUsingShallowClone` are possible, too.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] To localize defects, we want our attention to be focussed on relevant failing tests.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] This is why PHPUnit skips the execution of a test when a depended-upon test has failed.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] This improves defect localization by exploiting the dependencies between tests as shown in Example 2.12.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] A test may have more than one test dependency attribute.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] By default, PHPUnit does not change the order in which tests are executed, so you have to ensure that the dependencies of a test can actually be met before the test is run.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] A test that has more than one test dependency attribute will get a fixture from the first producer as the first argument, a fixture from the second producer as the second argument, and so on.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Whenever a test fails, PHPUnit tries its best to provide you with as much context as possible that can help to identify the problem.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] In this example only one of the array values differs and the other values are shown to provide context on where the error occurred.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] When the generated output would be long to read PHPUnit will split it up and provide a few lines of context around every difference.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] When a comparison fails PHPUnit creates textual representations of the input values and compares those.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] Due to that implementation a diff might show more problems than actually exist.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] This only happens when using `assertEquals()` or other “weak” comparison functions on arrays or objects.
[src:phpunit/writing-tests-for-phpunit] In this example the difference in the first index between `1` and `'1'` is reported even though `assertEquals()` considers the values as a match.
